        "text": "<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><h3>1) What is a rocker panel on a vehicle?</h3><p>A <strong>Rocker Panel</strong> is the lower body section beneath the doors, running between the front and rear wheel wells. It’s close to the ground and often exposed to road spray, debris, and corrosion—so lighting products installed there should be durable and weather-resistant.</p><h3>2) What are LED rocker panel lights used for?</h3><p><strong>LED Rocker Panel Lights</strong> improve side visibility, help define the vehicle’s footprint at night, and make it easier to see where you’re stepping when exiting the vehicle or working around it.</p><h3>3) Are rocker panel lights the same as underglow?</h3><p>They’re related but not always the same. Rocker panel lighting is typically positioned to illuminate along the rocker area for side visibility and practical use. Underglow often aims for a broader “under-vehicle” effect. Many setups combine both.</p><h3>4) Do rocker panel lights work on trucks with step bars?</h3><p>Yes—many installs are placed behind or along step bars for a clean look and added protection. The key is measuring your <strong>Rocker Panel</strong> area and choosing placement that avoids direct debris impacts.</p><h3>5) How do I choose the right rocker panel lighting length?</h3><p>Measure the area you want to illuminate and decide whether you want full-length coverage or targeted lighting near step points. Full-length installs improve side visibility; shorter segments can be ideal for practical step lighting.</p>",
        "heading_size": "medium",
        "text_alignment": "left"
      }
